ec.edu/brown/te/ALTERNATIVE_FUEL/TIMELINE/timeline.html Alternative Fuel Vehicles Timeline]\n* [http://www.econogics.com/ev/evhistry.htm An Extensive Electric Vehicle History]\n* [http://www.hybrid-vehicle.org/hybrid-vehicle-history.html Hybrid-Vehicle.org: Early Electric Cars]\n* [http://sloan.stanford.edu/EVonline/schallen.htm Analysis by Richard H. Schallenberg for the IEEE Transactions on Education]\n* [http://sloan.stanford.edu/EVonline/kirsch.htm 1997 Dissertation by David A. Kirsch, Stanford University]\n* [http://sloan.stanford.edu/EVonline/rae.htm \"1955 Business Analysis of Early Electric Vehicles\", John B. Rae, Associate Professor of History, MIT]\n* [http://www.didik.com/ev%5Fhist.htm History And Directory Of Electric Cars From 1834 to 1987]\n* [http://inventors.about.com/library/weekly/aacarselectrica.htm Short Electric, And Other Vehicle History]\n* [http://mikes.railhistory.railfan.net/r066.html Mikes Railway History, 1935: Electric Traction]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050901101724/http://www.hybridcars.com/history.html some Electric information as well]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071006044337/http://www.dassault.fr/filiale.php?docid=82 SVE Website]\n* [http://www.ElectricCarSociety.com/ Electric Car Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100718044715/http://www.evworld.com/index.cfm EV World -US Internet Journal about EVs]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/shows/223/electric-car-timeline.html Timeline: History of the Electric Car], [[Public Broadcasting Service]].\n* [http://www.techinsider.io/electric-cars-history-gif-2016-5 Watch how much electric cars have changed over time in one GIF], Tech Insider, May 2016.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of The Electric Vehicle}}\n[[Category:Electric vehicles|*]]\n[[Category:Historic electric vehicles|*]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "renumber duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_electric_vehicle"}
{"title_page": "Uncle Remus", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour           =\n| name             = Uncle Remus\n| series           =\n| image            = Uncle Remus crop, 1881.jpg\n| alt              =\n| caption          =\n| first            = ''Uncle Remus, His Songs and His Sayings: The Folk-Lore of the Old Plantation''\n| last             =\n| creator          = [[Joel Chandler Harris]]\n| portrayer        = [[James Baskett]] (''[[Song of the South]]'')\n| voice            =\n| lbl1             =\n| data1            =\n| lbl2             =\n| data2            =\n| lbl3             =\n| data3            =\n| info-hdr         =\n| noinfo           =\n| full_name         =\n| nickname         =\n| alias            =\n| gender           = Male\n| occupation       =\n| affiliation      =\n| title            =\n| family           =\n| spouse           =\n| significant_other =\n| children         =\n| relatives        =\n| religion         =\n| nationality      =\n| lbl21            =\n| data21           =\n| lbl22            =\n| data22           =\n| lbl23            =\n| data23           =\n| extra-hdr        =\n| lbl31            =\n| data31           =\n| lbl32            =\n| data32           =\n| lbl33            =\n| data33           =\n}}\n'''Uncle Remus''' is the fictional title character and narrator of a collection of black American folktales compiled and adapted by [[Joel Chandler Harris]] and published in book form in 1881. Harris was a journalist in post-Reconstruction [[Atlanta]], and he produced seven Uncle Remus books. He wrote these stories to represent the struggle in the [[Southern United States]], and more specifically in the plantations. He did so by introducing tales that he had heard and framing them in the plantation context. He wrote his stories in a dialect which was his interpretation of Deep South Negro language of the time. For these framing and stylistic choices, his collection has encountered controversy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montenyohl|first=Eric|date=1986|title=The Origins of Uncle Remus|journal=Folklore Forum|volume=18 |issue=2|pages=136\u2013167|hdl=2022/1941}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n[[File:Old Plantation Play Song, 1881.jpg|thumb|right|200px|\"Old Plantation Play Song\", from ''Uncle Remus, His Songs and His Sayings: The Folk-Lore of the Old Plantation'', 1881]]\n\n''Uncle Remus'' is a collection of animal stories, songs, and oral folklore collected from southern black Americans. Many of the stories are [[didactic]], much like those of [[Aesop's Fables]] and [[Jean de La Fontaine]]'s stories. Uncle Remus is a kindly old freedman who serves as a story-telling device, passing on the folktales like the traditional African [[griot]] to children gathered around him.\n\nThe stories are written in an [[eye dialect]] devised by Harris to represent a [[Deep South]] Negro dialect. Uncle Remus is a compilation of [[Br'er Rabbit]] storytellers whom Harris had encountered during his time at the Turnwold Plantation. Harris said that the use of the Negro dialect was an effort to add to the effect of the stories and to allow the stories to retain their authenticity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/whosafraidofsong0000kork|title=Who's afraid of the Song of the South? : and other forbidden Disney stories|last=Jim|first=Korkis|date=2012|publisher=Theme Park Press|others=Norman, Floyd.|isbn=978-0984341559|location=Orlando, Fla.|oclc=823179800|url-access=registration}}</ref> The genre of stories is the trickster tale. At the time of Harris's publication, his work was praised for its ability to capture plantation Negro dialect.<ref>{{cite news|work=Life on the Mississippi|date=1883|author=Clemens, Samuel L. |title=Chapter XLVII: 'Uncle Remus' and Mr. Cable}}</ref>\n\nBr'er Rabbit (\"Brother Rabbit\") is the main character of the stories, a character prone to tricks and troublemaking who is often opposed by [[Br'er Fox and Br'er Bear]]. In one tale, Br'er Fox constructs a doll out of a lump of tar and puts clothing on it. When Br'er Rabbit comes along, he addresses the \"[[Tar-Baby|tar baby]]\" amiably but receives no response. Br'er Rabbit becomes offended by what he perceives as the tar baby's lack of manners, punches it and kicks it, and becomes stuck.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/2306\n| title = Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings| publisher = www.gutenburg.org| accessdate = 2010-05-25| last =| first =| date = 2000-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nHarris compiled six volumes of ''Uncle Remus'' stories between 1881 and 1907; a further three books were published posthumously, following his death in 1908.\n\n* ''Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings'' (1881)\n* ''Nights with Uncle Remus'' (1883)\n* ''Uncle Remus and His Friends'' (1892)\n* ''The Tar Baby and Other Rhymes of Uncle Remus'' (1904)\n* ''Told by Uncle Remus: New Stories of the Old Plantation'' (1905)\n* ''Uncle Remus and Brer Rabbit'' (1907)\n* ''Uncle Remus and the Little Boy'' (1910)\n* ''Uncle Remus Returns'' (1918)\n* ''Seven Tales of Uncle Remus'' (1948)\n\n== Adaptations in film and other media ==\n[[File:Uncle Remus Disney screenshot.png|thumb|right|Uncle Remus as portrayed by [[James Baskett]] in ''[[Song of the South]]'']]\n\n<!--- NOTE: Only list things here that are direct treatments of the Uncle Remus stories. Do not list popular entertainment that mentions his name. All such will be deleted. --->\n===Comics===\nIn 1902, artist Jean Mohr adapted the ''Uncle Remus'' stories into a two-page comic story titled ''Ole Br'er Rabbit'' for ''[[The North American]]''.<ref name=FunnyAnimal-ch1>{{cite book |last1=Becattini|first1=Alberto|title=American Funny Animal Comics in the 20th Century: Volume One |date=2019 |publisher=Theme Park Press |location=Seattle, Washington |isbn=978-1683901860|chapter=Genesis and Early Development}}</ref>\n\nThe [[McClure Newspaper Syndicate]] released a ''Br'er Rabbit'' Sunday strip drawn by J. M. Cond\u00e9 from June 24 to October 7, 1906.<ref name=Holtz>{{cite book |last1=Holtz |first1=Allan |title=American Newspaper Comics: An Encyclopedic Reference Guide |date=2012 |publisher=The University of Michigan Press |location=Ann Arbor |isbn=9780472117567 |page=83}}</ref>\n\nAn ''Uncle Remus and His Tales of Br'er Rabbit'' newspaper [[Sunday comics|Sundays]]-only strip ([[King Features Syndicate]]) ran from October 14, 1945, through December 31, 1972, as an offshoot of the [[Disney comics]] strip ''[[Silly Symphony (comic strip)|Silly Symphony]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cartoonician.com/disneys-uncle-remus-strips/ |title=Disney's \"Uncle Remus\" strips|work=Hogan's Alley|number=16|date= 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304034715/http://www.cartoonician.com/disneys-uncle-remus-strips/|archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nThe stories have inspired at least three feature films:\n* [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Song of the South]]'' (1946), a combination of live action and animation with [[James Baskett]] as  Remus<ref>{{cite book|author=Brasch, Walter M. |date=2000|title=Brer Rabbit, Uncle Remus and the \"Cornfield Journalist\": The Tale of Joel Chandler Harris|publisher= Mercer University Press|page= 275}}</ref>\n* [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s film ''[[Coonskin (film)|Coonskin]]'' (1975), a satire of the Disney film which adapts the Uncle Remus stories to a contemporary [[Harlem]] setting\n* ''[[The Adventures of Brer Rabbit]]'' (2006), a direct-to video production with hip-hop influences<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/06/AR2006040602302.html| title = Child's Play| publisher = www.washingtonpost.com| accessdate = 2008-08-29\n| last =| first =| date = 2006-04-09}}</ref>\n'''TV'''\n*Brer Rabbit Tales (1991) by Emerald Hill Productions.\n\n=== Music ===\nUncle Remus appears heavily as a supporting character in [[The Residents]] Rock Opera, \"[[Not Available (album)|Not Available]]\", recorded in 1974 and released in 1978. After returning from [[Easter Island]], he provides unhelpful, dismissive advice to the lead character, quoting \"Well, strangers have left on longer trains before.\" in response to his cries for help and understanding.\n\n\"Uncle Remus\" is a song by [[Frank Zappa]] and [[George Duke]] from [[Apostrophe (')]] (1974), about the Joel Chandler Harris character.\n\nIn [[Bob Dylan]]\u2019s epic poem, [[Last Thoughts on Woody Guthrie]], the author lists several people that are commonly looked to for hope and inspiration, saying \u201cthat stuff ain\u2019t real.\u201d In one verse of the poem, he says \u201cAnd Uncle Remus can\u2019t tell you and neither can [[Santa Claus]].\u201d\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/last-thoughts-woody-guthrie/|title=Last Thoughts On Woody Guthrie - The Official Bob Dylan Site}}</ref>\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residents.com/historical/?page=notavailable|title=Not Available - Historical - The Residents|website=www.residents.com|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Uncle Remus characters]]\n* [[Tar-Baby]]\n*[[Magical Negro]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www2.gsu.edu/~wwwelf/elfjch.html |title=Joel Chandler Harris 1845 or 48 -- 1908|website=Eaton Literary Festival|location=Eatonton, Georgia}} Short biography of Joel Chandler Harris with photograph\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.bartleby.com/55/1.html |author=Roosevelt, Theodore |title=Theodore Roosevelt (1858\u20131919). An Autobiography. 1913 (Boyhood and Youth)}} References in Theodore Roosevelt's autobiography to Brer Rabbit and Uncle Remus.\n* {{cite web|title=William Ruhlmann|website= AllMusic |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/william-ruhlmann-mn0001799502}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource|Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings|Uncle Remus}}\n{{Commons category|Uncle Remus}}\n* Full text of [https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/author/868 books by Uncle Remus] from [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://www.uncleremusmuseum.org/ Official Uncle Remus Museum in Eatonton, GA]\n* [http://www.uncleremus.com/ Official Site of Uncle Remus]\n* {{librivox book | title=Uncle Remus | author=Joel Chandler HARRIS}}\n\n{{Uncle Remus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uncle Remus}}\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Black people in literature]]\n[[Category:Male characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1881]]\n[[Category:Fictional hares and rabbits]]\n[[Category:Fictional slaves]]\n[[Category:Fictional storytellers]]\n[[Category:Foxes in literature]]\n[[Category:Song of the South characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour           =\n| name             = Uncle Remus\n| series           =\n| image            = Uncle Remus crop, 1881.jpg\n| alt              =\n| caption          =\n| first            = ''Uncle Remus, His Songs and His Sayings: The Folk-Lore of the Old Plantation''\n| last             =\n| creator          = [[Joel Chandler Harris]]\n| portrayer        = [[James Baskett]] (''[[Song of the South]]'')\n| voice            =\n| lbl1             =\n| data1            =\n| lbl2             =\n| data2            =\n| lbl3             =\n| data3            =\n| info-hdr         =\n| noinfo           =\n| full_name         =\n| nickname         =\n| alias            =\n| gender           = Male\n| occupation       =\n| affiliation      =\n| title            =\n| family           =\n| spouse           =\n| significant_other =\n| children         =\n| relatives        =\n| religion         =\n| nationality      =\n| lbl21            =\n| data21           =\n| lbl22            =\n| data22           =\n| lbl23            =\n| data23           =\n| extra-hdr        =\n| lbl31            =\n| data31           =\n| lbl32            =\n| data32           =\n| lbl33            =\n| data33           =\n}}\n'''Uncle Remus''' is the fictional title character and narrator of a collection of black American folktales compiled and adapted by [[Joel Chandler Harris]] and published in book form in 1881. Harris was a journalist in post-Reconstruction [[Atlanta]], and he produced seven Uncle Remus books. He wrote these stories to represent the struggle in the [[Southern United States]], and more specifically in the plantations. He did so by introducing tales that he had heard and framing them in the plantation context. He wrote his stories in a dialect which was his interpretation of Deep South Negro language of the time. For these framing and stylistically choices, his collection has encountered controversy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montenyohl|first=Eric|date=1986|title=The Origins of Uncle Remus|journal=Folklore Forum|volume=18 |issue=2|pages=136\u2013167|hdl=2022/1941}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\n[[File:Old Plantation Play Song, 1881.jpg|thumb|right|200px|\"Old Plantation Play Song\", from ''Uncle Remus, His Songs and His Sayings: The Folk-Lore of the Old Plantation'', 1881]]\n\n''Uncle Remus'' is a collection of animal stories, songs, and oral folklore collected from southern black Americans. Many of the stories are [[didactic]], much like those of [[Aesop's Fables]] and [[Jean de La Fontaine]]'s stories. Uncle Remus is a kindly old freedman who serves as a story-telling device, passing on the folktales like the traditional African [[griot]] to children gathered around him.\n\nThe stories are written in an [[eye dialect]] devised by Harris to represent a [[Deep South]] Negro dialect. Uncle Remus is a compilation of [[Br'er Rabbit]] storytellers whom Harris had encountered during his time at the Turnwold Plantation. Harris said that the use of the Negro dialect was an effort to add to the effect of the stories and to allow the stories to retain their authenticity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/whosafraidofsong0000kork|title=Who's afraid of the Song of the South? : and other forbidden Disney stories|last=Jim|first=Korkis|date=2012|publisher=Theme Park Press|others=Norman, Floyd.|isbn=978-0984341559|location=Orlando, Fla.|oclc=823179800|url-access=registration}}</ref> The genre of stories is the trickster tale. At the time of Harris's publication, his work was praised for its ability to capture plantation Negro dialect.<ref>{{cite news|work=Life on the Mississippi|date=1883|author=Clemens, Samuel L. |title=Chapter XLVII: 'Uncle Remus' and Mr. Cable}}</ref>\n\nBr'er Rabbit (\"Brother Rabbit\") is the main character of the stories, a character prone to tricks and troublemaking who is often opposed by [[Br'er Fox and Br'er Bear]]. In one tale, Br'er Fox constructs a doll out of a lump of tar and puts clothing on it. When Br'er Rabbit comes along, he addresses the \"[[Tar-Baby|tar baby]]\" amiably but receives no response. Br'er Rabbit becomes offended by what he perceives as the tar baby's lack of manners, punches it and kicks it, and becomes stuck.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/2306\n| title = Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings| publisher = www.gutenburg.org| accessdate = 2010-05-25| last =| first =| date = 2000-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nHarris compiled six volumes of ''Uncle Remus'' stories between 1881 and 1907; a further three books were published posthumously, following his death in 1908.\n\n* ''Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings'' (1881)\n* ''Nights with Uncle Remus'' (1883)\n* ''Uncle Remus and His Friends'' (1892)\n* ''The Tar Baby and Other Rhymes of Uncle Remus'' (1904)\n* ''Told by Uncle Remus: New Stories of the Old Plantation'' (1905)\n* ''Uncle Remus and Brer Rabbit'' (1907)\n* ''Uncle Remus and the Little Boy'' (1910)\n* ''Uncle Remus Returns'' (1918)\n* ''Seven Tales of Uncle Remus'' (1948)\n\n== Adaptations in film and other media ==\n[[File:Uncle Remus Disney screenshot.png|thumb|right|Uncle Remus as portrayed by [[James Baskett]] in ''[[Song of the South]]'']]\n\n<!--- NOTE: Only list things here that are direct treatments of the Uncle Remus stories. Do not list popular entertainment that mentions his name. All such will be deleted. --->\n===Comics===\nIn 1902, artist Jean Mohr adapted the ''Uncle Remus'' stories into a two-page comic story titled ''Ole Br'er Rabbit'' for ''[[The North American]]''.<ref name=FunnyAnimal-ch1>{{cite book |last1=Becattini|first1=Alberto|title=American Funny Animal Comics in the 20th Century: Volume One |date=2019 |publisher=Theme Park Press |location=Seattle, Washington |isbn=978-1683901860|chapter=Genesis and Early Development}}</ref>\n\nThe [[McClure Newspaper Syndicate]] released a ''Br'er Rabbit'' Sunday strip drawn by J. M. Cond\u00e9 from June 24 to October 7, 1906.<ref name=Holtz>{{cite book |last1=Holtz |first1=Allan |title=American Newspaper Comics: An Encyclopedic Reference Guide |date=2012 |publisher=The University of Michigan Press |location=Ann Arbor |isbn=9780472117567 |page=83}}</ref>\n\nAn ''Uncle Remus and His Tales of Br'er Rabbit'' newspaper [[Sunday comics|Sundays]]-only strip ([[King Features Syndicate]]) ran from October 14, 1945, through December 31, 1972, as an offshoot of the [[Disney comics]] strip ''[[Silly Symphony (comic strip)|Silly Symphony]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cartoonician.com/disneys-uncle-remus-strips/ |title=Disney's \"Uncle Remus\" strips|work=Hogan's Alley|number=16|date= 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304034715/http://www.cartoonician.com/disneys-uncle-remus-strips/|archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nThe stories have inspired at least three feature films:\n* [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Song of the South]]'' (1946), a combination of live action and animation with [[James Baskett]] as  Remus<ref>{{cite book|author=Brasch, Walter M. |date=2000|title=Brer Rabbit, Uncle Remus and the \"Cornfield Journalist\": The Tale of Joel Chandler Harris|publisher= Mercer University Press|page= 275}}</ref>\n* [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s film ''[[Coonskin (film)|Coonskin]]'' (1975), a satire of the Disney film which adapts the Uncle Remus stories to a contemporary [[Harlem]] setting\n* ''[[The Adventures of Brer Rabbit]]'' (2006), a direct-to video production with hip-hop influences<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/06/AR2006040602302.html| title = Child's Play| publisher = www.washingtonpost.com| accessdate = 2008-08-29\n| last =| first =| date = 2006-04-09}}</ref>\n'''TV'''\n*Brer Rabbit Tales (1991) by Emerald Hill Productions.\n\n=== Music ===\nUncle Remus appears heavily as a supporting character in [[The Residents]] Rock Opera, \"[[Not Available (album)|Not Available]]\", recorded in 1974 and released in 1978. After returning from [[Easter Island]], he provides unhelpful, dismissive advice to the lead character, quoting \"Well, strangers have left on longer trains before.\" in response to his cries for help and understanding.\n\n\"Uncle Remus\" is a song by [[Frank Zappa]] and [[George Duke]] from [[Apostrophe (')]] (1974), about the Joel Chandler Harris character.\n\nIn [[Bob Dylan]]\u2019s epic poem, [[Last Thoughts on Woody Guthrie]], the author lists several people that are commonly looked to for hope and inspiration, saying \u201cthat stuff ain\u2019t real.\u201d In one verse of the poem, he says \u201cAnd Uncle Remus can\u2019t tell you and neither can [[Santa Claus]].\u201d\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/last-thoughts-woody-guthrie/|title=Last Thoughts On Woody Guthrie - The Official Bob Dylan Site}}</ref>\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residents.com/historical/?page=notavailable|title=Not Available - Historical - The Residents|website=www.residents.com|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Uncle Remus characters]]\n* [[Tar-Baby]]\n*[[Magical Negro]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www2.gsu.edu/~wwwelf/elfjch.html |title=Joel Chandler Harris 1845 or 48 -- 1908|website=Eaton Literary Festival|location=Eatonton, Georgia}} Short biography of Joel Chandler Harris with photograph\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.bartleby.com/55/1.html |author=Roosevelt, Theodore |title=Theodore Roosevelt (1858\u20131919). An Autobiography. 1913 (Boyhood and Youth)}} References in Theodore Roosevelt's autobiography to Brer Rabbit and Uncle Remus.\n* {{cite web|title=William Ruhlmann|website= AllMusic |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/william-ruhlmann-mn0001799502}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisource|Uncle Remus: His Songs and His Sayings|Uncle Remus}}\n{{Commons category|Uncle Remus}}\n* Full text of [https://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/author/868 books by Uncle Remus] from [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://www.uncleremusmuseum.org/ Official Uncle Remus Museum in Eatonton, GA]\n* [http://www.uncleremus.com/ Official Site of Uncle Remus]\n* {{librivox book | title=Uncle Remus | author=Joel Chandler HARRIS}}\n\n{{Uncle Remus}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uncle Remus}}\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Black people in literature]]\n[[Category:Male characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Fictional African-American people]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1881]]\n[[Category:Fictional hares and rabbits]]\n[[Category:Fictional slaves]]\n[[Category:Fictional storytellers]]\n[[Category:Foxes in literature]]\n[[Category:Song of the South characters]]\n", "name_user": "Global Cerebral Ischemia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncle_Remus"}
{"title_page": "RCGS Resolute", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = RCGS ''Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131992)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1992\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013)\n| Ship owner = [[Hanseatic Tours]] ([[Hapag-Lloyd]])<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship operator = Columbia Cruise Services GmbH\n| Ship registry = [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{flag|Portugal}} (2018\u2013)\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Rauma-Repola]] ([[Rauma]], [[Finland]])\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n*{{IMO Number|9000168}}\n*{{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*{{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship class = \n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = 1A Super\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}<ref name=\"euro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/hanseaticreview.htm |title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Review |publisher=Euro Lloyd |accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313135342/http://eurolloyd.com/hanseaticreview.htm |archivedate=2009-03-13 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf |title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details |publisher=Hapag-Lloyd |accessdate=2009-02-28 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' (previously '''''Society Adventurer''''' and '''''Hanseatic''''') is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[cruise ship]] previously operated by [[One Ocean Expeditions]] cruise line.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/vessels/vessel-rcgs-resolute |title=One Ocean Expeditions|accessdate=2018-10-05}}</ref> The vessel has been chartered as from October 2018 to One Ocean Expeditions of Canada and will cruise in the Antarctic and Arctic. According to the Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising and Cruise Ships, it was the only five-star expedition-cruise ship worldwide. Built in 1991, she specialises in trips to the [[Antarctic]]. She was built as ''Society Adventurer'', but was renamed when she was purchased by [[Hanseatic Tours]], as the fourth in a line of ''Hanseatic''s. In 1997, [[Hapag-Lloyd]] purchased Hanseatic Tours, and she passed into their fleet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html |title=Hanseatic Tours |last=Boyle |first=Ian |work=Shimplon Postcards |accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{expand-section}}\n\n===Drydock fire===\nOn June 13, 2013, the ship was in [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]], Germany when a fire broke out in the shipyard. This caused a delay in drydock and additional repairs were required and so the June 17 and July 4 sailings were cancelled.\n\n===Insolvency===\n''RCGS Resolute'' was scheduled to conduct a cruise to the Falkland Islands, South Georgia, and Antarctica from October 19, 2019, through November 6, 2019, beginning and ending in Ushuaia.  A medical emergency occurred on the ship while it was en route to Ushuaia, which delayed the ship, so the passengers were flown to Buenos Aires to meet the ship.  The ship sailed from Buenos Aires on October 19.  On October 22, the ship entered the port at Puerto Madryn to refuel.  After sitting in port for two days, it was revealed that the fuel could not be obtained because of non-payment by the ship operator, One Ocean Expeditions.  The Antarctic expedition was cancelled and the ship sailed back to Buenos Aires with all its passengers.  Once in Buenos Aires, the passengers disembarked and were left on their own with no reimbursement or compensation.  The ship was subsequently arrested in Buenos Aires for non-payment of debts. <ref>https://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Rcgs-Resolute-9000168.html</ref> At last report, the ship was still under arrest in Buenos Aires, having missed the entire 2019-2020 Antarctic season. <ref>https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates</ref>\n\n=== Collision with ANBV ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\nIn the early hours of 30 March 2020 ''RCGS Resolute'' was drifting just over {{convert|13|nmi}} off the coast of Isla La Tortuga, a Venezuelan island situated some 60 miles off the country's northern coast, when ANBV ''Naiguat\u00e1'', also known by its hull number GC-23, approached it. The Venezuelan Navy ship ordered the cruise ship to follow it to Puerto Moreno on Isla De Margarita, located to the east, accusing it of violating the country's territorial waters. Gun shots were fired and, shortly thereafter, the navy vessel approached the starboard side at speed with an angle of 135\u00b0 and purposely collided with ''RCGS Resolute''. The navy vessel continued to ram the starboard bow in an apparent attempt to turn the ship's head towards Venezuelan territorial waters. While the ''RCGS Resolute'' sustained minor damages, not affecting vessel's seaworthiness, the navy vessel suffered severe damages while making contact with the [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]] of the expedition cruise vessel ''RCGS Resolute'' and started to take water. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/ |title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident |work=Columbia Cruise Services}}</ref> Ultimately the ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank, leaving the 44 naval personnel to be rescued by another vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleetmon.com/maritime-news/2020/29297/cruise-ship-sunk-venezuelan-navy-ship-and-fled-pro/?fbclid=|title=Cruise Ship Sunk Venezuelan Navy Ship after being Fired at and Rammed. Don\u2019t mess with Resolute.|last=Voytenko|first=Mikhail|date=1 April 2020|website=Fleet Mon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n*[http://www.rcgsresolute.com/ RCGS Resolute Virtual Tour]<ref>{{cite web |title=One Ocean Dates and Rates |url=https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates}}</ref>\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=''RCGS Resolute''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = RCGS Resolute.jpg\n| Ship caption = RCGS ''Resolute'' in [[Aberdeen]] in June 2019\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship name = *''Society Adventurer'' (1991\u20131992)\n*''Hanseatic'' (1992\u20132018)\n*''RCGS Resolute'' (2018\u2013)\n| Ship owner = [[Hanseatic Tours]] ([[Hapag-Lloyd]])<ref name=\"seaweb\" />\n| Ship operator = Columbia Cruise Services GmbH\n| Ship registry = [[Madeira, Portugal|Madeira]], {{flag|Portugal}} (2018\u2013)\n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = 22 December 1989<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship builder = [[Rauma-Repola]] ([[Rauma]], [[Finland]])\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship yard number =306<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = 3 September 1990<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship launched = 5 January 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship completed = 7 June 1991<ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n|Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: CQAL6\n*{{IMO Number|9000168}}\n*{{MMSI|255806208}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n*{{ship register|DNV|G99209}}<ref name=\"dnv\">{{csr|register=DNV|id=G99209|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = In service\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = <ref name=\"dnv\" />\n| Ship class = \n| Ship tonnage =* {{GT|8,445}}\n* {{NetT|2,573}}\n* {{DWT|1,177}}\n| Ship displacement = \n| Ship length = {{convert|124.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship beam = {{convert|18.00|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = \n| Ship draft = {{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = 1A Super\n| Ship power = 2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[MaK]] 8M453C (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}2,940{{nbsp}}kW)<ref name=\"seaweb\">{{csr|register=SEAWEB|id=9000168|shipname=RCGS Resolute|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| Ship propulsion = Two shafts; [[controllable pitch propeller]]s\n| Ship speed = {{convert|16|kn}}<ref name=\"euro\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/hanseaticreview.htm |title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Review |publisher=Euro Lloyd |accessdate=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090313135342/http://eurolloyd.com/hanseaticreview.htm |archivedate=2009-03-13 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hapag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eurolloyd.com/Hapag-Lloyd/HANSEATIC.pdf |title=MS ''Hanseatic'' Ship details |publisher=Hapag-Lloyd |accessdate=2009-02-28 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n| Ship capacity = 184 passengers\n| Ship crew = 125\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''RCGS Resolute''''' (previously '''''Society Adventurer''''' and '''''Hanseatic''''') is a [[star (classification)|five-star]] [[cruise ship]] previously operated by [[One Ocean Expeditions]] cruise line.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/vessels/vessel-rcgs-resolute |title=One Ocean Expeditions|accessdate=2018-10-05}}</ref> The vessel has been chartered as from October 2018 to One Ocean Expeditions of Canada and will cruise in the Antarctic and Arctic. According to the Berlitz Complete Guide to Cruising and Cruise Ships, it was the only five-star expedition-cruise ship worldwide. Built in 1991, she specialises in trips to the [[Antarctic]]. She was built as ''Society Adventurer'', but was renamed when she was purchased by [[Hanseatic Tours]], as the fourth in a line of ''Hanseatic''s. In 1997, [[Hapag-Lloyd]] purchased Hanseatic Tours, and she passed into their fleet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html |title=Hanseatic Tours |last=Boyle |first=Ian |work=Shimplon Postcards |accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{expand-section}}\n\n===Drydock fire===\nOn June 13, 2013, the ship was in [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]], Germany when a fire broke out in the shipyard. This caused a delay in drydock and additional repairs were required and so the June 17 and July 4 sailings were cancelled.\n\n===Insolvency===\n''RCGS Resolute'' was scheduled to conduct a cruise to the Falkland Islands, South Georgia, and Antarctica from October 19, 2019, through November 6, 2019, beginning and ending in Ushuaia.  A medical emergency occurred on the ship while it was en route to Ushuaia, which delayed the ship, so the passengers were flown to Buenos Aires to meet the ship.  The ship sailed from Buenos Aires on October 19.  On October 22, the ship entered the port at Puerto Madryn to refuel.  After sitting in port for two days, it was revealed that the fuel could not be obtained because of non-payment by the ship operator, One Ocean Expeditions.  The Antarctic expedition was cancelled and the ship sailed back to Buenos Aires with all its passengers.  Once in Buenos Aires, the passengers disembarked and were left on their own with no reimbursement or compensation.  The ship was subsequently arrested in Buenos Aires for non-payment of debts. <ref>https://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Rcgs-Resolute-9000168.html</ref> At last report, the ship was still under arrest in Buenos Aires, having missed the entire 2019-2020 Antarctic season. <ref>https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates</ref>\n\n=== Collision with ANBV ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\nIn the early hours of 30 March 2020 ''RCGS Resolute'' was drifting just over {{convert|13|nmi}} off the coast of Isla La Tortuga, a Venezuelan island situated some 60 miles off the country's northern coast, when ANBV ''Naiguat\u00e1'', also known by its hull number GC-23, approached it. The Venezuelan Navy ship ordered the cruise ship to follow it to Puerto Moreno on Isla De Margarita, located to the east, accusing it of violating the country's territorial waters. Gun shots were fired and, shortly thereafter, the navy vessel approached the starboard side at speed with an angle of 135\u00b0 and purposely collided with ''RCGS Resolute''. The navy vessel continued to ram the starboard bow in an apparent attempt to turn the ship's head towards Venezuelan territorial waters. While the ''RCGS Resolute'' sustained minor damages, not affecting vessel's seaworthiness, the navy vessel suffered severe damages while making contact with the ice-strengthened bulbous bow of the ice-class expedition cruise vessel ''RCGS Resolute'' and started to take water. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.columbia-cs.com/statement-on-rcgs-resolute-incident/ |title=Statement on RCGS RESOLUTE incident |work=Columbia Cruise Services}}</ref> Ultimately the ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank, leaving the 44 naval personnel to be rescued by another vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleetmon.com/maritime-news/2020/29297/cruise-ship-sunk-venezuelan-navy-ship-and-fled-pro/?fbclid=|title=Cruise Ship Sunk Venezuelan Navy Ship after being Fired at and Rammed. Don\u2019t mess with Resolute.|last=Voytenko|first=Mikhail|date=1 April 2020|website=Fleet Mon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n*[http://www.rcgsresolute.com/ RCGS Resolute Virtual Tour]<ref>{{cite web |title=One Ocean Dates and Rates |url=https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates}}</ref>\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCollision with ANBV Naiguat\u00e1", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RCGS_Resolute"}
{"title_page": "A Great Big World", "text_new": "{{short description|American pop rock musical duo}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = A Great Big World\n|image           = A Great Big World 2014.jpg\n|caption         = A Great Big World in 2014\n|image_size      = 300px\n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = [[New York City]], [[New York State|New York]], United States\n|genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop rock]]|[[Pop music|pop]]}}\n|years_active    = 2011\u2013present\n|label           = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n|associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Christina Aguilera]]|[[Ingrid Michaelson]]}}\n|website         = {{URL|http://agreatbigworld.com/}}\n|current_members = \n* [[Ian Axel]]\n* Chad King {{small|(born Vaccarino)}}\n}}\n'''A Great Big World''' is an American musical duo from New York<ref>{{cite news | last =Lovett | first =Matthew | title =Preview: A Great big World At Rumba | newspaper =Columbus Alive | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 23 May 2013| url =http://www.columbusalive.com/content/stories/2013/05/23/preview-a-great-big-world-at-rumba.html | accessdate =4 June 2013 }}</ref> made up of singer/songwriters [[Ian Axel]] and Chad King and signed to [[Epic Records]]. The group is best known for their singles \"This Is the New Year\", which was performed by the cast in an episode of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' and reached the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|''Billboard'' Mainstream Top 40]] chart in May 2013,<ref>{{cite magazine | last =Caulfield | first =Keith | title =Bubbling Under: Passenger's Worldwide Ride Continues | magazine =Billboard Magazine | date = 17 May 2013| url =http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/chart-alert/1562813/bubbling-under-passengers-worldwide-ride-continues | accessdate =4 June 2013 }}</ref> and their international hit \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\", particularly after recording it as a duet collaboration with [[Christina Aguilera]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early beginnings===\n[[Ian Axel]] and Chad King met at [[New York University]], where they were attending the Steinhardt Music Program.<ref name=\"RockRevoltMay4\">{{cite news|last= |first= |title=A Great Big World To Release Three Song EP May 21 |newspaper=Rock Revolt Magazine |location= |pages= |language= |publisher= |date=4 May 2013 |url=http://www.rockrevoltmagazine.com/a-great-big-world-to-release-three-song-ep-may-21/ |accessdate=7 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507183047/http://www.rockrevoltmagazine.com/a-great-big-world-to-release-three-song-ep-may-21/ |archivedate=7 May 2013 |df= }}</ref> Both were music business students and Axel is said to have convinced King to write a song together. King agreed to work with Axel after hearing him sing. They both wrote and performed songs together prior to Axel embarking on a solo career in which he released an independent album featuring songs that were all co-written by King.<ref name=\"RockRevoltMay4\"/>\n\n===2011\u20132013: Breakthrough and ''Glee''===\nIn 2011, their song \"This Is the New Year\" was licensed to various television networks and was used as the theme song for [[MTV]]'s ''[[I Used to Be Fat]]'' as well as being featured on ''[[The Amazing Race]]'', [[ESPN]], [[One Tree Hill (TV series)|''One Tree Hill'']], and ''[[Good Morning America]]''.<ref name=\"ExaminerBigMoves\"/> Ian Axel and Chad King went on national tour and performed as the openers for [[Ingrid Michaelson]], [[Matthew Morrison]] (''Glee''), and [[Five for Fighting]].<ref name=\"RockRevoltMay4\"/>\n\nThe duo re-branded itself in 2012, when they took the official name ''A Great Big World''. They released a six-song EP after obtaining funding from the crowdsource funding website [[Kickstarter]].<ref name=\"ExaminerBigMoves\">{{cite news | last =Gibson | first =Yolanda | title =A Great Big World Is Making Moves This New Year| newspaper =Examiner | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =7 May 2013 | url =}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, \"This Is the New Year\" was performed by the cast in an [[Naked (Glee)|episode]] of [[Glee (TV series)|''Glee'']].<ref name=\"RockRevoltMay4\"/>\n\n===2013\u20132014: ''Is There Anybody Out There?''===\n[[File:A Great Big World Performing Live 2 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|A Great Big World performing in April 2014]]\nIn 2013, the group signed with [[Epic Records]] and released a three-song EP under the Epic label in May 2013.<ref name=\"ArtistDirect\">{{cite news | last = | first = | coauthors = | title =A Great Big World To Release \"This Is The New Year\" on May 21 | newspaper =Artist Direct | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =10 May 2013 | url =http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/a-great-big-world-to-release-three-song-ep-on-may-21/10550113 | accessdate =4 June 2013 }}</ref> They completed a headline tour in conjunction with their EP release.<ref name=\"AnnexMag\">{{cite news | last =Pikka | first = | coauthors = | title =Great Big World | newspaper =Annex Magazine | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date =2 May 2013 | url =http://www.annexmagazine.com/great-big-world/#sthash.EBQRnOfL.ZfHT7U4Y.dpbs | accessdate =7 May 2013 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130525055836/http://www.annexmagazine.com/great-big-world/#sthash.EBQRnOfL.ZfHT7U4Y.dpbs | archive-date =2013-05-25 | url-status=dead | df = }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, they were picked as [[Elvis Duran]]'s [[Elvis Duran's Artist of the Month|Artist of the Month]] and were featured on [[NBC]]'s ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]]'' where they performed live their song \"This Is the New Year\". The song \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\" was featured in the final episode of the US dance competition ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. season 10)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' on September 3, 2013 and released digitally the same day. It climbed to number 20 on iTunes in the United States the next day. The song was subsequently re-recorded featuring [[Christina Aguilera]] after she heard the song, and this version was released on November 4, 2013, and that version reached number 1 on the iTunes charts.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/11/03/a-great-big-world-christina-aguilera-say-something/ |title=A Great Big World feat. Christina Aguilera, 'Say Something' |date=November 3, 2013 |work=EW.com }}</ref> The following evening, A Great Big World and Aguilera gave the premiere live TV performance of the song on the NBC television series ''[[The Voice (U.S. season 5)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ryanseacrest.com/2013/11/01/christina-aguilera-duets-with-a-great-big-world-on-say-something/ |title=Christina Aguilera Duets With A Great Big World on 'Say Something' |author=Kathleen Perricone |date=November 1, 2013 |work=RyanSeacrest.com }}</ref> The song reached No. 1 on the digital song chart the next day with 189,000 copies sold for the week.<ref name=billboard>{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5785918/eminem-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-celine-dion-and-avril-lavigne-in-top |title=Eminem Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200, Celine Dion and Avril Lavigne in Top Five|author= Keith Caulfield |date= November 13, 2013 |work=Billboard }}</ref> The video was released on November 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/music/140996_Say_Something_Music_Video_A_Great_Big_World_Featuring_Christina_Aguilera/ |title=World Premiere: 'Say Something' Music Video |author= Robert Pace |date= November 19, 2013 |work=ETonline }}</ref> In November 2013, it was announced that A Great Big World would be performing at the annual ''[[Victoria's Secret Fashion Show]]''. The same month, they performed for the first time at the American Music Awards with Aguilera.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5800696/a-great-big-world-christina-aguilera-combine-to-say-something-at|title=A Great Big World, Christina Aguilera Combine To 'Say Something' At American Music Awards |author= Jason Lipshutz |date= November 24, 2013 |work=Billboard }}</ref>\n\nTheir debut album, ''[[Is There Anybody Out There? (album)|Is There Anybody Out There?]]'', was released on January 21, 2014.\n\nThe group made an appearance on the song \"Over You\" on [[Ingrid Michaelson]]'s 2014 album, ''Lights Out''.\n\n\"Say Something\" was also used in the nineteenth season of South Park (Episode 6) Titled \"Tweek x Craig\"\n\n===2015: ''When the Morning Comes''===\nOn April 21, 2015, it was announced through the A Great Big World Facebook page that Ian and Chad were working on a second album. The group announced the release of their first single off of the new album via Instagram in mid-July. The single \"Hold Each Other\" was released on July 22, 2015, featuring the rapper Futuristic. The non-rap version was released on July 24, 2015. The album was released on November 13, 2015, with the title ''[[When the Morning Comes (A Great Big World album)|When the Morning Comes]]''. While visiting the UK in June 2015 they recorded at Sarm Studios in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AGreatBigWorld/status/609764814236315649 |title=A Great Big World on Twitter: \"Recording @SarmStudios in London today. New music is coming\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-06-13 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref> Several musicians and producers collaborated on the album including [[Dave Eggar]], Derek Fuhrmann, [[Gregg Wattenberg]], [[Greg Holden]], [[Kevin Kadish]], [[Josh Kear]], [[Dan Romer]] and [[Mozella]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AGreatBigWorld/status/619601083107831808 |title=A Great Big World on Twitter: \"Working with the incredible @daveeggar on some new music!\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-07-10 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AGreatBigWorld/status/607652839322710017 |title=A Great Big World on Twitter: \"Making some magic with these guys @DerekAEF #greggwattenberg #agreatbigalbum \" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-06-07 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AGreatBigWorld/status/603348188129579008 |title=A Great Big World on Twitter: \".@Dan_romer is totally blowing it \" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-05-26 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AGreatBigWorld/status/588856122104107008 |title=A Great Big World on Twitter: \"Just finished writing a beautiful song w/ @mozellamusic. Can't wait to share what we've been working on with you all. \" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=2015-04-16 |accessdate=2015-08-10}}</ref>\n\nThey have been writing a musical for several years. The show is about family and is called ''Strokes of Genius''.<ref name=\"Out\">{{cite web|title=Chad King of A Great Big World discussing about loving a man |journal=Out |date=14 August 2015 |url=http://www.out.com/music/2015/8/14/chad-king-great-big-world-discusses-singing-about-loving-man3 |accessdate=2 September 2015 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Sales\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"US200\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/5885925/a-great-big-world/chart?f=305|title=A Great Big World \u2013 Chart history: Billboard 200|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=A+Great+Big+World |title=Discography A Great Big World |publisher=Australian Charts Portal. Hung Medien |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123071041/http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=A+Great+Big+World |archivedate=2015-01-23 |df= }}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br /><ref name=\"AUT\">{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=A+Great+Big+World|title=Discographie A Great Big World|publisher=Austrian Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br /><ref name=\"CANAlbums\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/5885925/a-great-big-world/chart?f=309|title=A Great Big World \u2013 Chart history: Canadian Albums|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br /><ref name=\"SWE\">{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=A+Great+Big+World|title=Discography A Great Big World|publisher=Swedish Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br /><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/a%20great%20big%20world/|title=A Great Big World - Official Charts Company | publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] | accessdate=March 21, 2014 | format=select \"Albums\" tab}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Is There Anybody Out There? (album)|Is There Anybody Out There?]]''\n|\n* Released: January 21, 2014\n* Label: [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* Format: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Compact disc|CD]]\n| 3 || 33 || 36 || 3 || 25 || 16\n|\n* US: 165,000<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151029235059/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= October 29, 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS 